# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ban-johnson-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ban-johnson-park/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Originally known as **Whittington Park**, the ballpark was the Spring training site for numerous Major League Baseball teams, hosting spring training games and served as home for Hot Springs minor league teams.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Over 130 Major League Baseball Hall of Fame inductees played at Whittington Park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1918, Babe Ruth, then a pitcher for the Boston Red Sox, hit a 573-foot home run at the park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The park was also home to the ever first Umpire School.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1935, Whittington Park, was renamed after Hall of Fame baseball pioneer Ban Johnson, founder of the American League.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Beginning with the spring of 1886, when the Chicago White Stockings' (today's Chicago Cubs) President Albert Spalding, the founder of A.G Spalding, and player/manager Cap Anson brought their players to Hot Springs, Arkansas.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The concept was for the players to have training and fitness before the start of the regular season.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] This move gave credit to Hot Springs being called the "birthplace of spring training baseball".
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Both Spalding and Anson, liked the city and the natural springs for their players.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] They first played in an area behind what is now the Garland County Courthouse on Ouachita Avenue and was called the **Hot Springs Baseball Grounds**.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1894 Whittington Park opened as a replacement for the Hot Springs Baseball Grounds.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Along with Majestic Park, built in 1909, and nearby Fogel Field, built in 1912, Hot Springs developed training venues to meet the demand for Major League teams.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Later, another venue, Sam Guinn Field was built in 1933 at 497 Crescent Avenue to host Negro leagues spring training.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The original playing field was estimated to be between 500–600 feet (150–180 m) to center field.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1910, the original grandstand was demolished and home plate moved, giving the field shorter dimensions.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1938, the right field fence was heightened by 15 feet (4.6 m) because right field distance was only 260 feet (79 m).
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Over 130 Major League Baseball Hall of Fame players, including Babe Ruth, Cy Young, Cap Anson, Honus Wagner, Ty Cobb, Tris Speaker, Walter Johnson, Rogers Hornsby, Mel Ott, Jimmie Foxx, Stan Musial and Satchel Paige were involved in training or spring training games at Whittington Park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The park was also utilized by the House of David teams, and for baseball schools.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The bearded House of David traveling baseball team used Whittington Field and Hot Springs for their training site.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Major League teams training at Whittington Park between 1896 and 1926 were the Cleveland Spiders, Chicago Cubs, St.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Louis Cardinals, Pittsburgh Pirates, Detroit Tigers, New York Yankees, Brooklyn Dodgers and Boston Red Sox.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Whittington Park was home to the Negro league Hot Springs Arlingtons from 1896 to 1903 and the Hot Springs Blues in 1904.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Patrick's Day, 1918, is nicknamed the "Day that changed Baseball Forever".
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] On that day, Babe Ruth hit a long Home Run into the Arkansas Alligator Farm and Petting Zoo.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The story goes that on March 17, 1918, Babe Ruth, then an accomplished 23-year-old Boston Red Sox left-handed pitcher, altered the course of baseball history.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Red Sox first baseman Dick Hoblitzel was unable to play in the opening exhibition game against Brooklyn at Whittington Park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Ruth (coming off a 24–13 season) was a last minute replacement at first base, his first time at a position other than pitcher.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Ruth would hit two long home runs that day while playing the field for the first time.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] His first home run was a long blast that landed in a wood pile.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] However, his second Home run is legendary in its record setting length and eventual effect on Ruth.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] It was a grand slam, a shot that traveled an astonishing estimated 573 feet (175 m), sailing out of the park, across the entire span of Whittington Avenue, landing in a pond the alligator farm across the street.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Amazingly, Ruth would prove it was no fluke as he hit another home run into the alligator farm a week later, while pitching for the Red Sox.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] On March 15, 2011, an event was held to recognize and celebrate the famous Ruth home run at the site.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Bill Jenkinson, a noted baseball historian was part of the event, visited the site and helped to authenticate the 573-foot (175 m) home run.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] About the home run distance, Jenkins said, "No one can confirm it with complete certainty, but the data points in that direction.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Ruth's performance that day at Whittington Park led to a change in Ruth's career and a major change in baseball history.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] As a result of his hitting, the Red Sox began rethinking Ruth's dual abilities during and after 1918.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] To begin, Ruth would alternate in the 1918 season, pitching less and playing the field often.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] His dual abilities helped lead the Red Sox to the 1918 World Series Championship.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Hitting more regularly in 1918, Ruth hit a league leading 11 home runs to go with a 13–7 record (and two wins in the Series).
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Eventually Ruth stopped pitching and became a hitter, with results of legend that exploded after his 1920 sale to the New York Yankees: Lifetime, .342 average; 714 Home Runs; 2062 RBI'S; 2174 Runs Scored; 1.164 OPS.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Along with hosting eight Major League teams, Whittington Park was the home to Hot Springs minor league teams.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The Hot Springs Bathers played in the Cotton States League from 1938 to 1941 as an affiliate of the Chicago Cubs (1938) and the Detroit Tigers (1939-1941) and an earlier team called the Bathers played in the Arkansas State League in 1894 and 1897 and the Southwestern League in 1898.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The Hot Springs Vaporites (1908–1909) and Hot Springs Vapors (1906) also played in the Arkansas State League.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Doan operated the "All-Star Baseball School" at the park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The "school" attracted thousands of younger players, with 1938 topping at 450 attendees.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Instructors included: Rogers Hornsby, Grover Cleveland Alexander, Red Faber, Dizzy Dean, George Sisler, Bob Feller, Tris Speaker and Burleigh Grimes.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Attendees included legendary female athlete Babe Didrickson, who attended in 1934, after already being an Olympic Gold Medalist in the 1932 Summer Olympic Games.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Future Major League player Sam Narron also enrolled.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1936, Doan installed lights at the park to begin night usage and games.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] To coincide with Doan's "baseball School", Major League Umpire George Barr operated his **George Barr Umpire School**, which is recognized as the first ever umpire instructional school.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Future Major League Umpires Bill McKinley and Scotty Robb were attendees.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1939, Hornsby took over for Doan and started the **Rogers Hornsby Baseball College**.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Hornsby's operation was housed at Majestic Field, but utilized Whittington Park and other fields in Hot Springs, including Whittington Park and Fogel Field, which was located behind the Alligator Farm.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Hornsby's "college" would attract 100-200 prospective professionals, with scouts present, for six week sessions.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Hornsby had legendary instructors: Cy Young, Jimmie Foxx, Tris Speaker and Schoolboy Rowe.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] After World War II halted many baseball leagues, the Bathers were gone and Major League teams had moved to warmer climates for spring training.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Louis Browns and Pittsburgh Pirates outlined plans to move their spring training from California to Ban Johnson Park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] However those plans never materialized and the future use of Ban Johnson Field was affected.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] In 1947, with no baseball tenants, the ‘Whittington Park Speedway’ racetrack began operation on the site.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] To replace Ban Johnson Field, Jaycee Park was built at the Majestic Field site on the corner of Belding Avenue and Carson Street.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Later, from 1948 to 1951, the Chicago White Sox would return Spring training to Hot Springs, utilizing Jaycee Field as their training site.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The Pittsburgh Pirates trained for over a decade at Whittington Park.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Hall of Fame shortstop Honus Wagner became a fixture in the city.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] As evidence of this Wagner purchased and donated basketball uniforms and equipment to Hot Springs High School in 1912.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The uniforms were in the Pittsburgh Pirates colors of black and gold and subsequently the high school switched permanently to those colors.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Wagner also refereed a basketball game for the school that season, something he would later repeat.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Whittington Park and Ruth's home run are featured prominently in the Documentary *The First Boys of Spring* (2015).
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Produced by Larry Foley, the documentary on Hot Springs spring training is narrated by actor Billy Bob Thornton, a Hot Springs area native.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The documentary began airing nationally on the MLB Network in February, 2016.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] "Baseball Trail Park" at 1201 Whittington Ave. is part of the City of Hot Springs Park System.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] It is named in tribute to the Hot Springs Historic Baseball Trail and the ball fields that once existed nearby: Sam Guinn Field, Whittington Park and Fogel Field.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Today, the Whittington Park/Ban Johnson Park site is an asphalt parking lot for the Weyerhaeuser Company.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] There is a home plate marker in the parking lot.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] A section of cement bleachers remains visible in the adjacent hillside.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The cement bleachers on the side of the hill was a fan section called the "Wolves Den".
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] The Arkansas Alligator Farm and Petting Zoo is still across the street with a marker for the landing spot of Ruth's St.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Artifacts related to Ban Johnson Park are on display at the Hot Springs Baseball Museum.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] On March 24, 2018, a ceremony was held at the Whittington Park site to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the Babe Ruth home run.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Related events included Hall of Fame inductee Ferguson Jenkins and former All-Star Al Hrabosky, as well as noted baseball historians Bill Jenkinson and Tim Reid.
[src:ban-johnson-park/ban-johnson-park] Today, there are four plaques at the site as part of the **Hot Springs Historic Baseball Trail**: Whittington Park, Mel Ott, Honus Wagner and Babe Ruth.
